(42, 9, 52, 40, 10, 5, 5, 'village of the Samaritans', 'Samaritan Mission Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the sending of messengers or disciples. In Luke, Jesus sends messengers to a Samaritan village, while in Matthew, he instructs his disciples not to enter any city of the Samaritans.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 52, 12, 17, 24, 33, 'village of the Samaritans', 'Connection of Samaritans and Preparation', 'This connection highlights the theme of preparation and reception in Samaria. In both passages, there is an emphasis on the interactions with the Samaritans, where messengers are sent to prepare for Jesus, paralleling the Assyrian actions of sending priests to teach the people in Samaria.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 52, 42, 10, 1, 1, 'sent messengers before his face', 'Sending Messengers Before Him', 'Both passages emphasize the act of sending messengers ahead of Jesus. In Luke 9:52, messengers are sent to prepare a village, while in Luke 10:1, the Lord sends seventy others to prepare cities for his arrival.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 52, 42, 10, 33, 33, 'village of the Samaritans', 'Compassion in Samaritan Context', 'This connection highlights the role of Samaritans in both passages. In Luke 9:52, the messengers enter a Samaritan village, setting the stage for the Samaritan''s compassion in Luke 10:33.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 52, 43, 8, 48, 48, 'village of the Samaritans', 'Samaritan Identity Connection', 'This connection highlights the identity of Samaritans in both passages. In Luke, Jesus interacts with Samaritans, while in John, the Jews label him as a Samaritan, indicating a shared cultural context.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 52, 15, 4, 1, 5, 'make ready for him', 'Preparation and Opposition in Building', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of preparation for a significant task, with Luke highlighting the sending of messengers to make ready, while Ezra describes the adversaries'' attempts to disrupt the rebuilding of the temple. This connection highlights the challenges faced when undertaking a divine mission.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 52, 39, 3, 1, 1, 'make ready for him', 'Preparation for the Lord''s Coming', 'This connection highlights the theme of preparation for the Lord''s arrival. Both passages emphasize the role of messengers sent to prepare the way for the Lord.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 53, 43, 4, 9, 9, 'did not receive him', 'Jews and Samaritans'' Hostility', 'This connection highlights the rejection faced by Jesus in both passages. In Luke, the Samaritans do not receive him due to his journey to Jerusalem, while in John, the woman notes the animosity between Jews and Samaritans.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 53, 43, 4, 40, 42, 'did not receive him', 'Samaritan Reception of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the contrasting receptions of Jesus in Samaria. In Luke, he is initially rejected, while in John, the Samaritans embrace him and believe in him as the Christ.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 53, 42, 9, 48, 48, 'receive him', 'Receiving Jesus and His Message', 'This connection highlights the theme of reception in both passages. In Luke 9:53, the rejection of Jesus contrasts with the call in Luke 9:48 to receive others in His name, emphasizing the importance of welcoming those who represent Him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 54, 12, 1, 10, 14, 'command fire to come down from heaven', 'Connection of Divine Fire', 'Both passages emphasize the calling down of fire from heaven as a demonstration of divine authority. The disciples reference Elijah''s actions, indicating a thematic link between their desire for judgment and Elijah''s prophetic power.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 54, 59, 1, 19, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Wrath and Response', 'This connection highlights the theme of wrath in both passages. In Luke, the disciples express a desire for wrath through fire, while James advises being ''slow to wrath,'' emphasizing a contrast in responses to provocation.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 54, 59, 3, 14, 18, NULL, 'Wisdom and Strife Connection', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the desire for violent retribution in Luke and the call for peace and mercy in James. Both passages emphasize the consequences of strife and the importance of wisdom from above.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 54, 44, 4, 29, 30, 'command fire to come down', 'Divine Power and Boldness', 'This connection highlights the theme of invoking divine power. In Luke, the disciples seek to call down fire, while in Acts, they ask for boldness and healing through God''s power.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 54, 10, 21, 2, 2, 'command fire to come down', 'Divine Judgment and Zeal', 'This connection highlights the theme of zeal for God''s honor, as seen in both passages. In Luke, the disciples express a desire for divine retribution, while in 2 Samuel, Saul''s zeal leads to violence against the Gibeonites.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 54, 12, 10, 31, 31, 'command fire to come down', 'Divine Judgment and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of invoking divine judgment. In Luke, James and John seek to call down fire, similar to the actions of Jehu, who disregards God''s law despite his authority. Both passages emphasize the use of divine power in response to sin.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 54, 66, 13, 3, 3, NULL, 'Divine Judgment and Healing', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention in both passages. In Luke, the disciples seek to call down fire for judgment, while in Revelation, the beast''s deadly wound being healed suggests a miraculous restoration, evoking the power of God in contrasting ways.', 'theme', 0.293, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 55, 18, 2, 10, 10, 'what manner of spirit ye are of', 'Spirit and Response to Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of one''s spirit in response to adversity. In Luke, the rebuke addresses a misunderstanding of the spirit, while Job''s response reflects wisdom amidst suffering.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 55, 18, 26, 4, 4, 'what manner of spirit ye are of', 'Connection of Spirit in Context', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of spirit and understanding. In Luke, the rebuke highlights a lack of awareness regarding the spirit''s nature, while Job questions the source of one''s words and spirit.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 55, 40, 16, 23, 23, 'Ye know not what manner of spirit ye are of', 'Rebuke of Misguided Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize a rebuke directed at misunderstanding. In Luke, Jesus addresses a misguided spirit, while in Matthew, he rebukes Peter for not aligning with God''s purposes.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 55, 60, 3, 9, 9, 'what manner of spirit ye are of', 'Spirit and Response to Evil', 'This connection highlights the theme of responding to hostility with a spirit of blessing rather than retaliation. Both passages emphasize the importance of understanding one''s spirit and choosing a positive response in the face of negativity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 55, 66, 3, 19, 19, 'rebuked them, and said', 'Rebuke and Chastening Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of rebuke in both passages. Luke 9:55 speaks of a rebuke related to understanding one''s spirit, while Revelation 3:19 emphasizes rebuke as an expression of love and a call to repentance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 55, 24, 17, 9, 9, 'what manner of spirit ye are of', 'Deceitfulness of the Heart', 'This connection highlights the nature of human spirit and heart. Both passages emphasize the idea that human understanding can be flawed and wicked.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 55, 40, 26, 51, 51, 'what manner of spirit ye are of', 'Spirit and Violence Connection', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the spirit of the disciples and the violent action taken by one of them. In Luke, Jesus rebukes the disciples for their misunderstanding of their spirit, while in Matthew, one disciple acts violently, demonstrating a lack of understanding of Jesus'' teachings.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 56, 40, 20, 28, 28, 'not come to destroy men’s lives', 'Connection of Purpose in Ministry', 'Both passages emphasize the mission of the Son of man to save lives and serve others. Luke highlights the saving aspect, while Matthew focuses on ministering and giving his life as a ransom.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 56, 43, 3, 17, 17, 'to save them', 'Salvation Focus in Both Passages', 'Both passages emphasize the purpose of Jesus'' mission as one of salvation rather than condemnation. They highlight the intention to save lives and the world, contrasting with destruction or condemnation.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 56, 45, 12, 21, 21, 'to save them', 'Overcoming Evil with Good', 'This connection highlights the theme of salvation and the call to respond to evil with good. In Luke, Jesus emphasizes His mission to save lives rather than destroy them, while Romans encourages overcoming evil through good actions.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 56, 42, 19, 10, 10, 'to save them', 'Connection of Salvation Purpose', 'Both passages emphasize the mission of the Son of man to save lives. Luke 9:56 states He came to save, while Luke 19:10 specifies seeking and saving the lost.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 56, 43, 10, 10, 10, 'to destroy men’s lives', 'Connection of Life and Salvation', 'Both passages emphasize the purpose of Jesus'' mission to bring life rather than destruction. Luke 9:56 highlights saving lives, while John 10:10 contrasts this with the thief''s destructive intent.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 9, 56, 40, 18, 10, 10, 'to save them', 'Connection of Salvation and Care', 'This connection highlights the theme of valuing lives and the importance of saving rather than destroying. Both passages emphasize the care for individuals, particularly the vulnerable, as seen in the reference to ''little ones'' in Matthew.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
